text:
thank you so so much @farrahsnz for these awesome awesome products for us to try. miss t was so super excited to open her package addressed to her. we have struggled on a daily basis to get this little monkey to eat "proper" food, and she would eat rice bubbles for breakfast lunch and dinner if i let her. we found these packet of wraps which tara calls the dinosaur wraps which she loved but would only eat peanut butter on them. then we found the chicken farrah's meal box and she absolutely loved them, and i was able to put lettuce, cucumber, red onion ans cheese on them, which she will now eat quite regularly. it can be a struggle as a parent of a child with special needs especially when it comes to sensory issues, but all i can say is keep trying, give it time, you never know they might surprise you.

text:
this. so much this. it‚Äôs been a heartbreaking week on this topic - both nationally and locally. it is time for churches (and christians) to realize that sexual abuse is a crime. and is not, and never has been, something that should be handled by the church alone. 
the excuse that ‚Äúit will hurt people‚Äù or ‚Äúruin people‚Äôs view of church‚Äù is not only sickening, but theologically wrong. 
how we deal with sin is supposed to be the difference between christians and the ‚Äúworld‚Äù. it‚Äôs never a set back for jesus when the truth comes out. it is always a set back when truth is hidden. 
we have a choice - to deal with abuse openly and honestly - and make a church safe and healthy place. or we can keep doing what‚Äôs been done - and replicate pain, destruction, and alienation. 
the choice is ours. it‚Äôs time to speak out. the time has come to stop putting discomfort, and a distorted view of ‚Äúgrace‚Äù over truth.

to every victim who has chosen to speak out: thank you! i am with you. and i will fight for you. #metoo #churchtoo #endabuse

text:
the burned house - in the burned house i am eating breakfast.
you understand: there is no house, there is no breakfast,
yet here i am.

the spoon which was melted scrapes against 
the bowl which was melted also.
no one else is around.

where have they gone to, brother and sister,
mother and father? off along the shore,
perhaps. their clothes are still on the hangers,

their dishes piled beside the sink,
which is beside the woodstove
with its grate and sooty kettle,

every detail clear,
tin cup and rippled mirror.
the day is bright and songless,

the lake is blue, the forest watchful.
in the east a bank of cloud 
rises up silently like dark bread.

the burned house - in the burned house i am eating breakfast.
you understand: there is no house, there is no breakfast,
yet here i am.

the spoon which was melted scrapes against 
the bowl which was melted also.
no one else is around.

where have they gone to, brother and sister,
mother and father? off along the shore,
perhaps. their clothes are still on the hangers,

their dishes piled beside the sink,
which is beside the woodstove
with its grate and sooty kettle,

every detail clear,
tin cup and rippled mirror.
the day is bright and songless,

the lake is blue, the forest watchful.
in the east a bank of cloud 
rises up silently like dark bread.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates suppoed by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

that‚Äôs what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him ‚Äúwe can take it.‚Äù no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it‚Äôs a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then it‚Äôs easy to come along for the ride. there‚Äôs no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they‚Äôre both just characters on the television.

that‚Äôs what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it‚Äôs not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it‚Äôs that we‚Äôve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
when i was invited by curator kari conte, director of programs and exhibitions at iscp and francesco urbano ragazzi, directors of the chiara fumai archive, to take part of the reenactment of the performance the s.c.u.m. elite (2014)created by chiara fumai for her solo exhibition less light here in nyc, i didn‚Äôt realize that this would be one of the hardest works i have participated (despite going through two different undergraduate theater schools, professional plays, and being performing for 7 years now). perhaps because one work requires you to study why it exists in the world in first place-and this one was really really deep and complex. perhaps because i want to make justice to the brilliancy of a piece created by a young artist who no longer lives among us. perhaps because i did have to dive into the study of radical feminism to understand why i am holding a gun for an hour as a quiet almost invisible permanent threat to others or perhaps because i grew up in a patriarchal house with guns all over the wall for display and hunt use and now, i think this is was a crazy way to grow up. perhaps because i also refused all that, that patriarchy, and left. finally, perhaps because we have a tremendous amount of work to do still. and the work will take time, a lot of  time and a steady fight to get there. i learned how absurd it was to be in this piece just as the way we still live as women.
photo by @donnaclearyartandherbalism „Éª„Éª„Éª
-

text:
this is something i needed to share. 
my father sexually abused me until the age of 17. i finally told someone, and was swept into a world of court and law. eventually, my father was sent to prison hopefully for the rest of his life. 
i get a call about a week ago. ‚Äúyour father is dying. if you want to come see him, the time would be now.‚Äù what do i do in this situation? should i go see him? tell him i forgive him? no! why should he have the satisfaction of dying with my forgiveness?? this man ruined my childhood, and he deserves to rot in hell for it. my mom and other family members can go see him if they want, but his daughter will not be in attendance. 
#sexualassault #metoo

text:
vanessa tyson, the california professor who has accused virginia lt. gov. justin fairfax of sexually assaulting her at the democratic national convention in 2004 in boston, will meet with the prosecutor's office in massachusetts to detail her allegations, her lawyer said wednesday.

a second woman has accused fairfax of raping her when they were both students at duke university in 2000; he has denied both allegations.

suffolk district attorney rachael rollins said she was ready to investigate tyson's allegations, the boston globe reported tuesday. the globe also reported that a spokeswoman for fairfax, lauren burke, said he would cooperate with an investigation if a criminal complaint is filed but may file his "own criminal complaint in response." tyson's attorney debra s. katz called burke's statement that fairfax could initiate charges against tyson "a shocking threat." photo: vanessa tyson speaks as part of a talk, "betrayal and courage in the age of #metoo," at stanford university's center for advanced study in the behavioral sciences on feb. 12, 2019. (nikki ritcher/center for advanced study in the behavioral sciences )

text:
i try not to put people up on pedestals. we‚Äôre all human. and i am well aware that ryan adams was never rumored to be an angel. i never had him on a pedestal but i‚Äôve loved his music, all of his music, since i first heard ‚Äúsylvia plath‚Äù and saw him at the first ever acl festival. he‚Äôs an incredible talent and this was a hard dose to take today. his albums are mounted on my walls. he‚Äôs in my mix daily. but, as a survivor of childhood sexual abuse, i am compelled to say what i need to say and hope people understand why we need to talk about it. 
for those who don‚Äôt know or understand, what the @nytimes describes ryan doing (among other things) is called ‚Äúsexual grooming‚Äù and it is a criminal offense (see pics in post) though i don‚Äôt believe he is being officially charged at the moment. he denies the claims and says he didn‚Äôt know anyone was underage despite cited text messages that imply otherwise. if you‚Äôre interested, you can look up the article and read for yourself what each party says. we‚Äôll see how it unfolds over time but, in the interest of preventing abuse and/or trafficking that is often the result of grooming, please visit the american bar association website for important information at bit.ly/abagrooming 
as for me, i‚Äôll be grappling with my feelings over this as a survivor, a mom, a flawed human being, a longtime fan, a songwriter, a woman in the music industry, etc., etc. #survivor

text:
the 2019 women's follows the 2017 women's march and 2018 women's march. in early 2017, during the aftermath of president trump's election, around four million people gathered in washington dc for the first women's march, a protest against legislation and rhetoric that harms women. however, news reports from across north america noted that turnout for the 2019 women's march was lower compared to previous years, with potential reasons being poor weather, a decline in interest and controversy over protest organization in the united states.

the 2019 women's follows the 2017 women's march and 2018 women's march. in early 2017, during the aftermath of president trump's election, around four million people gathered in washington dc for the first women's march, a protest against legislation and rhetoric that harms women. however, news reports from across north america noted that turnout for the 2019 women's march was lower compared to previous years, with potential reasons being poor weather, a decline in interest and controversy over protest organization in the united states.
(photo by daniel rad)
in order to see the entire image please see the profile.

text:
our society is shallow and mostly unawakened, it‚Äôs all about programming you to think you‚Äôre not enough so you feel bad about yourself so you buy the sh*t they‚Äôre selling so you can fix yourself.

news flash, you‚Äôre not broken and you never have been.

all the superficialness does is keep you disconnected from your own soul, your own truth, your own self love, and your own inner beauty.

we think we‚Äôre the bodies, but we‚Äôre not, they‚Äôre just human suits for our souls to play in, they‚Äôre not who we are, yet we spend lifetimes obsessing over them and trying to look and be good enough.

but for who?

you were born worthy.

you were born beautiful.

you were born with the gift of your infinite heart and soul to shine.

to me and any conscious man, you‚Äôve always been beautiful, you open the heart chakra of the planet, you radiate love, you make the world a better place.

don‚Äôt worry so much about how your temporary human suit looks, focus on knowing that you are perfect and beautiful and loved exactly as you are.

don‚Äôt compare yourself to anyone.

own your power.

i believe in you.

i see you.

tag a friend who needs to hear this.

@scottbrandonhoffman .
.

posted @withrepost ‚Ä¢ @frizzkidart ‚Äúanother lil we believe survivors piece i made for @ryesassl what is the importance of saying ‚Äúwe believe survivors‚Äù and what does it mean? it doesn‚Äôt mean that we don‚Äôt believe in evidence or the importance of due process. it means that we recognize how common sexual violence is, and how difficult it is for survivors of sexual violence to be treated fairly by the police and by the court systems, which are inherently oppressive institutions that are complicit with patriarchy. when i say ‚Äúwe believe survivors‚Äù it‚Äôs a way of me telling folks of all genders who have experience sexual violence that i hear you, i believe you, i know that this did in fact happen to you and i will support you whether you choose to speak out on it or whether you choose to keep that story to yourself for whatever reason. are there false accusations? yes there are. it‚Äôs estimated to be a very small percentage, somewhere between 2 - 8%. this means that‚Äôs the vast majority of allegations of sexual violence are true. 
how can we hold space for survivors/victims of sexual violence? check in with friends who are survivors when there‚Äôs a lot of stuff in the news about sexual violence. be clear about your boundaries and ask others on what their boundaries are? think about the ways you‚Äôve been complicit in rape culture. we have all held toxic and problematic views at some point in our lives (i know i have held some harmful views in the past) and we must continue to unlearn these views and grow by listening to the lived experiences of others.‚Äù

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaign‚Äôs use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people‚Äôs profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there ‚Äúcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheating‚Äù. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesday‚Äôs hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytica until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
~ as the #metoo movement and the subject of sexual misconduct in all its incarnations gained momentum and increasingly became part of the current zeitgeist, or public consciousness, i found myself thinking. not so much thinking, as following a hunch that there was more to this than meets the eye. you all know by now that i am the kind of domme who likes to dig for things below the surface. so, too, when it came to the issue of the widespread violence against women, it seemed to me far too facile to simply label men as sexual predators and, having slapped that label on them, to just leave it at that. i am experienced enough to know what happens when we dismiss people as wild, nasty animals who need to be tamed, and let‚Äôs just say that it isn‚Äôt helpful at all and only creates further division.

without my intention, i had a sudden insight about the matter when i was in at the sauna with a group of women. somehow, as women do, we got to talking about our first sexual encounters and of our mental processes at the time of their occurrence. as it turned out, most of us had had a first sexual experience when we were about thirteen. by ‚Äòsexual experience‚Äô i do not mean sexual intercourse but rather the initial moment in which we suddenly gained the understanding that some other human being is regarding us and relating to us in a sexual way ‚Äì flirting, touching, manipulating, convincing, desiring‚Ä¶ 
the problem we all seemed to share was that, at the time, we lacked any understanding of this situation whatsoever. in other words, at the age of 13 we did not know whether it was up to us to decide to allow anyone to touch us in a sexual way, or not to. my body ‚Äì my temple, and similar discourse had, unfortunately, not been part of our mental arsenal. which in turn resulted in total confusion when faced for the first time with being approached in a sexual manner. all of us, it turned out, had no idea when to say yes and when to say no. or how to say no, or whether it was okay to. being so ill-equipped in this interpersonal exchange had the effect of creating an even more distorted view of our sexuality... ~

text:
alles is liefde
voor wie dat wil
en voor wie nog durft te dromen
over wonderlijke prinsen op witte paarden
die niet goed kunnen rijden
en hun geheimen lang bewaarden
en alles is ook liefde
voor wie stilletjes verlangt
alles is liefde
alles is liefde
voor iemand zoals jij
voor hem, voor haar, voor mij

sinds ik weet dat ik deze maand een column schrijf voor het gooisch blad met als onderwerp ‚Äúalles is liefde‚Äù zingt dit lied van blof vaak in mijn hart. alles is inderdaad liefde al is het woord liefde ook verwarrend omdat de meeste mensen liefde beschouwen in relatie tot de ander. 
maar over wat voor liefde wil ik het hier dan hebben? ik wil het hebben over de liefde die voorbijgaat aan woorden en concepten. de liefde die voorbijgaat aan ieder geloof en elk gevoel. de liefde die voorbijgaat aan alles wat we kennen. de liefde die voorbijgaat aan relaties en iedere scheiding. er is niets te ‚Äòkrijgen‚Äô in deze liefde want deze liefde is de oorsprong van het bestaan: de stille aanwezigheid. deze liefde is alles. deze liefde ben jij! 
het leven is best wel liefdevol voor mij geweest de afgelopen vijftig jaar; ik kreeg daardoor de mogelijkheid om naar binnen te mogen reizen . de enige weg om deze liefde te ervaren is namelijk om naar binnen te reizen in ons eigen hart.  tijdens die weg naar binnen heb ik o.a wijze hulp gehad van de eeuwenoude yoga beoefening .  en natuurlijk is het voor degenen die een vredige jeugd hebben gehad en onvoorwaardelijke liefde hebben ontvangen veel makkelijker, maar het is in principe voor iedereen mogelijk om in dat liefdesveld te vertoeven. ik heb persoonlijk geen verschrikkelijke dingen meegemaakt; geen #metoo ervaringen , ik ben geboren uit liefde en was zeer gewild door beide ouders, ik had en heb een liefdevolle familie & vrienden, ik trouwde jong met mijn grote liefde en kreeg twee gezonde kinderen. 
na de geboortes van onze kinderen voelde ik heel sterk waarvoor ik geboren was. moeder zijn en onvoorwaardelijke liefde mogen voelen & delen. ik heb altijd in sprookjes kunnen geloven en droomde van mijn prins op het witte paard. 
de eerste keer in het leven dat ik echt diepe pijn voelde was o lees verder op facebook als je wil #love ‚ù§Ô∏è

text:
today in black sistory we honor the silence:

we the silent screams of our foremothers
the screams swallowed 
while we were raped 
the screams tucked into the darkest places 
of our souls 
so as not to wake the children 
and see more horror in their eyes 
so as not to wake the men 
and see the pain of not being able to protect us 
the emasculation of being powerless 
when master rapes your wife 
we the sobs hushed 
we the refrains muffled 
we the words that didn‚Äôt part from our teeth 
because 
we did best to know our place 
we did best not to be uppity 
or think that we may deserve dignity 
we that learned a down cast eye 
kept us alive 
we the tears flowing like waterfalls 
perpetually inside 
while our sons swung 
high 
and died 
our feet bleed beneath our skin 
our backs shredded within 
our lips closed and tight 
our tongue tattooed with perpetual bite 
we learned to suffer in silence to save ourselves
to save our men and children 
we learned too well 
we the tired 
we the weary
we the screams
we the sirens
we are silent no more 
you will hear us 
our feet marching 
with the screams of our ancestors at our backs 
like wind in our sails 
vengeance that has laid waiting for too long 
we will open our mouths 
and you will never hear the same again 
our screams will echo in your souls forever 
our #metoo began before hollywood 
before trump grabbed pussies 
stand with your alabaster tears 
for as long as you can 
but move when you hear my army 
move when you hear my battle cry 
move when you feel the presence of my lineage 
silent no more --lesl√© honor√©
________________________________________

text:
always, always remember you are more powerful than you can imagine.
.
your voice is only scary to those who know they‚Äôve done wrong and now have a lot to lose.
.
speak your truth. even when your voice shakes. even when the adversary becomes stronger and more powerful.
.
someone recently told me, ‚Äúa lion is the most aggressive when it‚Äôs the most vulnerable.‚Äù
.
the louder their roar, the more they have to lose and will intimidate, threaten and convince others to betray in order to protect the aggressor and status quo. only when we use our voice can we end the cycle of violence and bring about justice. i‚Äôve been through the fire. 20 months of anxiety, panic, depression and ptsd. i‚Äôve done the work to heal from my sexual assault. it was messy and i will forever have triggers. you are never the same after abuse. ever. but now that i‚Äôve stepped into my power and am raising my voice, i‚Äôm going to forever be an advocate for the real survivors of this world who are healing themselves from sexual, physical or physiological abuse. you are never as broken as you feel and you are most definitely not alone.
.
remember the song ‚Äúfight song‚Äù:
i may only have one match, but i can make an explosion. üî•
.
#mystoryisntoveryet #metoo #timesup

share your empowerment story!
.
reposted from @theodoraayeni -  empowered women empower others! üíØ

call it girl power! sisterhood! your tribe! you big sister! teacher! 
whatever name you call it, truth is we all need a little external pumpüôÑ motivation and inspiration... and here's my tale of one of such you got me all pumped moment! 
growing up in kaduna and choosing to be an educator just seem at the time like i had lost my path! my dad said to me straight up ...you better be the best teacher i knowüòÅüôÑ now 13 years after school and tons of exciting teacher experiences under my belt i hope he thinks i was right! lol

but that's not the gist! in a bid to hopeful redirect me at the time my dad arranged a meeting with mrs audifferen and contrary to what everyone expected her to say she loaded me with ideas on the right channels to take if i sure wanted to be a distinguished teacherüòÅüòÅüòÅ and now look what has come out of it! and yes mrs audifferen is old and grey and in her late eighties and still gets tickled i became a teacher true true !ü§£ü§£ but hey! we all need that lamp light ahead of us... not necessarily to give us all the solutions but to share the path, the secrets and boom we will become so much light ourselves. 
let's do this together me ladies, let's empower others!  to keep the sisterhood going you need to share the oil of experience, knowledge and exposure... join me and other ladies around the world as we commit to sharing of ourselves with the world for sustainable growth in girl tribe ! 
be deliberate! 
#empoweredwomenempoweredothers
#empoweredforsustainability
#thefutureofafricanwomenisnow
#awlcrwanda2019

to ta z ksiƒÖ≈ºek, kt√≥rƒÖ powinny przeczytaƒá wszystkie kobiety. mo≈ºe to zbyt g√≥rnolotnie zabrzmi... ale... mass media od lat bombardujƒÖ nas wizerunkami piƒôknych kobiet, kt√≥rych jedynymi atutami sƒÖ d≈Çugie (koniecznie d≈Çugie) w≈Çosy, nienaganna figura i zniewalajƒÖcy u≈õmiech. kobietƒô spycha siƒô do kategorii rzeczy, (piƒôknych dzie≈Ç) s≈Çu≈ºƒÖcych do zaspokajania mƒôskich fantazji. zapytaj samƒÖ siebie - do jakiego idea≈Çu dƒÖ≈ºysz? obawiasz siƒô wyj≈õƒá nieumalowana z domu?dlaczego zawsze musisz chowaƒá siƒô za maskƒÖ make-upu? dbasz o figurƒô dla swojego zdrowia czy mo≈ºe tak naprawdƒô chcesz siƒô przypodobaƒá mƒôskim gustom i robisz wszystko, by byƒá zauwa≈ºonƒÖ? je≈õli robisz to dla siebie, to ≈õwietnie, ale bƒÖd≈∫my nie tylko ≈Çadne, lecz takze odwa≈ºne, by g≈Ço≈õno mowiƒá o kondycji kobiety w dzisiejszym ≈õwiecie. a≈º 20 lat uplynelo do chwili, w kt√≥rej rose mcgowan g≈Ço≈õno opowiedziala swojƒÖ historiƒô. fragmenty jej powstajƒÖcej ksiƒÖ≈ºki by≈Çy kradzione, bo wielcy ludzie hollywood obawiali siƒô tego co ma do powiedzenia jedna z ofiar modowo-filmowego ≈õwiata, w kt√≥rym w≈Çadzƒô sprawujƒÖ bogaci panowie w garniturach. rose niejednokrotnie molestowano, wpychano w kanon piƒôkna, kt√≥remu musia≈Ça sprostaƒá. by dostaƒá rolƒô w filmie trzeba byƒá przecie≈º "mi≈ÇƒÖ"... po latach trwania w "hollywoodzkiej sekcie" obciƒô≈Ça swoje d≈Çugie, piƒôkne w≈Çosy i zaczƒô≈Ça m√≥wiƒá o tym co przesz≈Ça, teraz jest g≈Çosem wielu skrzywdzonych, molestowanych i zgwa≈Çconych kobiet.

text: "our systems are neurobiologically wired to fear vulnerability‚Äîespecially if we have experienced any kind of trauma. when life hands us experiences that encompass a degree of uncertainty and unpredictability, our systems often respond from fear because that feels vulnerable, and our bodies have been wired to register that space as a threat to our survival. but as adults, the place of the unknown not life threatening, and in fact can be the birthplace innovation, creativity, possibility and opportunity. when we find ourselves unable to sleep at night because we don‚Äôt know what‚Äôs going to happen (in our relationships, or jobs, with our children etc) it is because our antiquated wiring is alerting us to eminent danger. having faith that things will turn out alright is not what i am suggesting‚Äîin fact things don‚Äôt always turn out alright and our attachment to a particular outcome keeps us in a place of suffering. but having faith that you will survive however things turn out is the path to healing. in fact, it is often the path to thriving and becoming fully alive." #loveyourself #love #traumarecovery #faith #strength #resilience #yoga #mindfulness #metoo #community #healing

one billion rising

nach der weltgesundheitsorganisation gilt sexualisierte gewalt gegen frauen weltweit als eines der gr√∂√üten gesundheitsrisiken f√ºr frauen. der heutige tag will auf dieses thema aufmerksam machen.
viele frauen* haben schon erfahrungen mit dem thema sexualisierte gewalt gemacht. die grenzen der betroffenen person werden dabei stark verletzt. 
j√§hrlich kommt es bundesweit zu 12000-13000 anzeigen, doch die dunkelziffer liegt deutlich h√∂her. aus einer studie aus dem jahr 2014 geht hervor, das 35% der frauen ab dem 15. lebensjahr in deutschland bereits opfer von sexualisierter/k√∂rperlicher gewalt durch ihre partner*in oder durch eine fremde person geworden sind. 
durch verschiedene hashtags wurde das thema aus der tabuzone geholt, etwas durch #ichhabenichtangezeigt, #ichhabeangezeigt, #aufschrei, #metoo und zuletzt durch #whyididn'treport. betroffene brachen ihr schweigen und solidarisierten sich untereinander. 
nun zu dem heutigen tag - one billion rising.

text:
working with dreams in the studio today, mixed media, acrylic paint, pencil, biro, marker pens.  i am experimenting with overlaying imagery and narrative.  it‚Äôs good to be making art, i really recommend it! it saves me from myself! 
i‚Äôm not sure what i would do if i didn‚Äôt have this outlet! when i was a teenager my art got processed through fashion - my outlet then was the make-up, hair and clothes i wore, my masks. working in the fashion business for many years my art/creative outlet was my business.  i kept it small so it was manageable and that way i could bring my art into the business - painting the flyers to advertise the events or bringing ideas to my team meetings in the morning, we used to experiment with chanting together.  i think my team thought i had lost my marbles! 
how do you bring your creativity into your every day? .

text:
15 year old lauren üëÜüèºüëÜüèº i was in 9th grade. i lived in a loving, christian home. i was an athlete, a high honors student, a sister, a daughter, and a friend. i had never so much as kissed a boy. ‚ú® this is who i was when i was first sexually assaulted. no longer a little girl, but not quite a woman. my parents, my sister, and i were avid churchgoers. we attended every sunday (and 2-3 other times during the week for various activities). that church was my family. it was my home. we could not have known the evil that lived inside the four walls of that church. we could not have known that a youth leader would take advantage of my young teenage body - and claim something from me that was not his to claim. i fight every day to find the safety in my own skin that i once had. i fight to reclaim the things that he stole from me... all those years ago. sweet 15 year old lauren, i wish things had been different for you. but i am here now, fighting to tell your story üíñ

money raised through fundraising efforts in 2019, will support the campaign and the victims of sexual violence & their children; many of which live in poor rural communities and suffer from low levels of literacy and poor access to education, healthcare and other social services.

text:
this is a love letter, to me.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
here we are today, 10 months, 9 experts + 10 modules later.  healingher.co is ready to be shared with the world, so we can work towards a beautiful ending together.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i chose this day to launch because whether single or in a romantic relationship, it can bring up all kinds of uncomfortable feelings.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
when those hard feeling came up i found myself trying to escape by numbing out with drinks or food; avoiding the pain.  for someone who fears being stood up, i never realized how often i don't show up for myself. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
this platform is an invitation to show up for yourself with self-compassion, self-forgiveness, and self-acceptance.  this is a chance for you to rewrite your love letter, exactly the way you deserve. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
on this valentine's day, we are offering you the gift of radical self-love.  do you accept? #healingher

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text: so 5 yrs ago from today, i was at the er getting stitches while a good friend cried and told me he couldn't watch me destroy myself anymore.  i didn't how i'd stop, but knew that had to be the last time.  after 16 yrs of spending a ridiculous amount of energy actively destroying myself, i saw my current coach @shaneearlyaz  compete at the copper classic and asked my trainer at the time if he thought i could be on that stage in 2016.  after that day, i redirected that energy into tearing my body down to rebuild it as a stronger self.  this has given valentine's day a new meaning for me and now i take that day every year to celebrate a recovery that started with one different choice.  i once had a professor who used to say, "it's never too late to make another choice," so what will yours be?  #recovery #selfinjuryawareness #takebackthenight #sexualassaultawareness #figurecompetitor #bodypositive #transformation #womenwholift #powerliftingwomen #metoo #bethere #nomore #beaware

text:
this picture and frame sits on my desk where i can see it every day. ...
when i feel like giving up on something .. when i get uber frustrated and start to throw my hands up over it .. i see this picture and it makes me take a pause. ...
then i say a quick prayer, take a deep breath and i remember who i am!  i see my little girl and i recall how far she has come and i put back into perspective the smallness of whatever is stealing my joy in the moment. ...
and i forge forward again.  and i succeed!
...
don‚Äôt ever forget who you are, friends!  say a prayer, take a breath and remember who you are so you can forge forward to success!

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

text:
fran√ßoise gilot (french, born 1921), "la r√©ponse," ca. 1965‚Äì1966, oil on canvas, sold at christie's in 2016.  real talk: 
i've been mulling on the disappointing and upsetting new york times profile of a prominent musician's treatment of women and thinking about the complications of separating a creator from their creations.  can you compartmentalize between an artist's behavior and their art?  i really can't, and it's ruined a lot of paintings and music for me.  one of the sadnesses of studying art history is learning the sordid backstory behind so many celebrated artists, and realizing how many talented creators were sidelined for years or sometimes forever by being deemed "muses" (continued in comments)

text:
click the link in my bio to read the rest... there‚Äôs not a day that goes by that i don‚Äôt think about the women‚Äôs hearts i‚Äôve broken, the friends that have walked away from me because i was selfish, or the family members that won‚Äôt talk to me because i was an asshole. there‚Äôs also not a day that goes by that i don‚Äôt think about being told i am useless, that no one loves me, and that i am broken. the difference between now and then is that i don‚Äôt believe the things that other people wanted to portray me to be. i create my own narrative. that‚Äôs not to say that i haven‚Äôt had my moments that‚Äôs just to say that everything will change and it starts inside. at least for me, it did. 
when i look in the mirror, i‚Äôm proud of the person that i see now. i am ok with living as i am. i will make mistakes, i will learn lessons, and i will continue to strive to be better in the hopes that one valentines day in the future as i look into the eyes of the person that i am with i get to know that they get the 100% authentic and honest me. i do sit and contemplate these things, and i remind myself that if the tin man can get a heart then so can i. it‚Äôs baby steps, and i‚Äôm proud of who i am today.

text:
this is what it was like...
it was my first time seeing the #narcissist since learning i was pregnant. he arrived at my home 4 hours late, drugged out of his mind, pushed me onto the hardwood floor & raped me.
my head was banging against the glass of my balcony door.
the narc was so violent that he broke my necklace & an earring; bits of gold scattered all over the floor. he even broke off strands of my hair.
the narc was baring his teeth during this, like an animal. üò•üò•
i felt i had no idea who this person even was (in actuality he was revealing his real self for the first time).
when i told the narc to stop, to leave me alone, he snarled: ‚Äúyou love this dirty sex on the floor. you love it!‚Äù
.
.
.

then the narc ran to the bathroom, performed an #islamic ablution ritual (how can someone like this claim to be a #muslim???)
unsurprisingly, i was crying uncontrollably. the narc‚Äôs response: ‚Äúyou read too much into this relationship. i was just having fun. i never intended to spend my entire life with you.‚Äù
i‚Äôve no idea what this comment had to do with him raping me. 
he‚Äôd said he was coming over to have a talk about my pregnancy.
the narcissist then stormed out of my apartment to drive home to his mommy.
his entire ‚Äúvisit‚Äù to my home had lasted approximately 20 minutes.
his final words were: ‚Äúyou‚Äôll probably have a miscarriage.‚Äù
.
.
.
i spent the next 5 hours sitting at my desk, tears streaming down my face, too numb to get up & go to bed.
i called the police. next thing i knew i had a social worker calling me & eventually showing up unannounced at my apartment. she‚Äôd been tipped off by police that i was pregnant by a drug-addicted #rape suspect who had a criminal record and was ‚Äúknown‚Äù to police.
.
.
.
this episode wasn‚Äôt even the worst thing he did to me. but it stood out because of the level of contempt & violence the narc displayed towards his own unborn child. 
as my pregnancy progressed i had to watch the narcissist continue to con people. he runs a store selling incense & dishes out ‚Äúspiritual‚Äù advice to unsuspecting customers. none of them know he‚Äôs a convicted crack dealer, cocaine addict, deadbeat dad & rapist. 
continues in commentsüëáüëá

text:
the best valentine's day ever because i finally decided to stop waiting for a man to love me and instead decided to stop destroying myself with alcohol on february 7, 2017. i used aa and holistic healing i learned @passagesmalibu 
there is no reason to limit the type of help you need to heal. i used cannabis everyday for a healing tool and it helps me. i paid off all my debt, got promoted, lost 70 pounds and became a yoga teacher but in aa this means i am not sober but to me it means i am living my best life. everyone should have access to the plants they feel help them live their best lives. 
alcohol was killing me 
cannabis heals me
let's change the way we view addiction and end the stigma attached to alcoholics and substance abuse in our country now. 
help your friend, tell your brother to stop drinking alcohol and get sober. i am only here because my brother screamed at me to stop drinking 
i am so fortunate to have a brother like that, who actually changed and then inspired me to do the same üíì 
in a shocking turn of events i have found gratitude and compassion for @realdonaldtrump . his brother died from alcohol addiction and mine is alive. it helps me understand his pain, we all have painful past but we can heal. i hope he can find the light one day ‚òÄ

text:
the students of howard university film and television program call for the establishment of a department of cinematic arts and television, effective fall 2019. howard has the most comprehensive film program, and offers the only mfa in film, of any hbcu in the united states. howard university has the only minority owned pbs affiliate in the nation. for decades since the founding of the film program in 1971, we have been fulfilling a national and global need for women storytellers and storytellers of color. still, there is no hbcu in the united states with a department dedicated to the study of cinematic arts and television - we can change this.

we are calling for the first department of cinematic arts and television, at any hbcu in the nation, to include the following components:

a) independently administered budget. 
b) independently managed equipment center and facilities. 
c) shared governance by the students and faculty over said budget, equipment center, curriculum development and implementation of the undergraduate and graduate bfa and mfa programs, as well as program and instructor evaluation. 
d) and a commitment to attract more of the most qualified professors in the industry, and to continue to produce graduates of the finest caliber.

support us by signing the petition, share the campaign with everyone you know, and let howard university president wayne a. i. frederick know that the time is now for a howard university department of cinematic arts and television.

since 1971, the howard university film program has produced and/or supported the most highly trained and widely acclaimed storytellers, including: bradford young, hans charles, ernest dickerson, arthur jafa, jenn nkiru, malik sayeed, alan ferguson, sehkar kammula, faraday okoro, lodi matsetela, lekgetho makola, nijla mumin, maori karmael holmes, floyd rance, yao ramesar, and shirikiana aina.

with the likes of stanley nelson, michelle parkerson, julie dash, and haile gerima having served as faculty in the program.

in the new era of #oscarssowhite, #timesup, and #metoo the film and television industry is clearing space to #tellblackstories. we must be prepared to answer the call.

text: after years of recording noticeable progress in the fight against hiv/aids in sub-saharan africa, new hiv infections are recorded. this is due to a new generation of adolescents that never witnessed the full ravages of the disease, hence an increase in risky sexual behaviours. now the national aids council (nac) considered lobbying the government for a policy that makes hiv testing mandatory for couples planning to marry. click the link in our bio to read more about the ambivalences for human rights involved in these kind of attempts to control the disease.

this book explores a time in the life of tise, a young and beautiful girl, her love for modelling and her near death experience. it talks about the strained relationship between tise and her mum and how no matter how much tise strived to please her mum, she never seemed to do enough. it also explores friendship in its pure state between tise and her friend chichi. ''not all heroes wear capes,'' but this wasn't revealed till the book's end. it also addressed other topics that are not freely discussed but is beginning to gain attention in the african society, topics like depression and suicide. to read, kindly click link in bio and first two chapters are free for download in bio as well. also available on amazon.

dear survivor,‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

text: read my new column ‚Äî ‚Äúhollywood's hijack of the #metoo movement.‚Äù in the wake of the #metoo movement, people are immediately rushing to judgment and to punishment of any accused individual ‚Äî in many cases, without due process. naturally, this moblike mentality to blindly punish an accused individual has the potential for far-reaching negative consequences ‚Äî namely, collateral damage to the falsely accused by those who misuse the movement for their own ambitious aims. take, for example, the domestic abuse allegations against johnny depp, which should serve as a cautionary tale. depp is a beloved actor who has won 14 people's choice awards. he is, by all accounts, a serial monogamist. his first wife and three decades' worth of long-term girlfriends uniformly characterize him as a sensitive and caring partner...visit the link in my bio for the full story. #johnnydepp

text:
‚Äúdear survivor, healing is not a destination but a practice.‚Äù üíå by amita swadhin, director of mirror memoirs ‚ú® art by jess x snow & layqa nuna yawar ‚ú® #survivorloveletter  was founded by tani ikeda [description: a queer brown gender non-conforming survivor looks up into the night sky. inside their portrait is a burnt down forest and their little self hugging themselves as wildflowers bloom all of their body. the quote above is handwritten . ]

here is a beautiful excerpt from amita‚Äôs extended #survivorloveletter : ‚Äúeverything in nature is here to teach you, if you can learn to open to the lessons: the ocean is changed but not defined by an oil spill. the wind is changed but not defined by a nuclear explosion. the dog is changed but not defined by the fighting pit.
healing is not a destination, but a practice and an understanding. one day you will learn to wear your wounds instead of being led by them. your spirit will expand far past the edges of your pain. you will understand suffering as a universal human experience, and power as the ability to feel joy and pleasure despite what you have endured. 
most of all, your wounds will disrupt the experience of time as linear. you and i will be able to use them to connect across time and space, because the body (and the psyche) truly does keep the score. i will visit you many times over, integrating each moment of fear, by holding your hand, rocking you, letting you weep in my arms ‚Äì i will grow up to understand how to love you in all the ways you always needed and never received. 
one day i will look at old photos of you: skinny brown girl with the big head and bigger glasses, teeth too large, knees too skinned, hair too scraggly, gender too mixed ‚Äì and marvel that what once looked ugly and spoiled looks only precious and tender and beautiful. 
i will always be with you, just as you will always be with me, until each memory is felt and released, until we are truly one.‚Äù #believesurvivors #lgbtqia #queerart #queer #lgbtq #metoo #metoosurvivorsmarch

i will always be with you, just as you will always be with me, until each memory is felt and released, until we are truly one.‚Äù

text:
our new #survivorloveletter by bamby salcedo, with art by beyon üíå

bamby salcedo is a nationally recognized latina trans activist & president of translatina coalition . 
beyon wren moor is a cree/ukrainian trans woman artist, musician, tattoo artist living in pocumtuck (western mass). download our posters for free at survivorloveletter.com [description: a silhouette of a trans latinx woman with constellations across her face. roses grow from her chest. handwriting says: ‚Äúdear trans sibling survivor, with tears, determination, heart and courage, you can overcome. only you can give the gift of life to yourself." ]

here is an excerpt from bamby‚Äôs letter: ‚Äúif i can say anything to you today with this letter, is that, i understand the struggle of feeling guilty. i hope that you also see and understand that you are a precious being, you are perfect just the way you are. you have been created to exist in this world and to live your life to the fullest of your potential despite the horrible experiences that you may have encounter when you were sexually assaulted. please do not let any of your horrible experiences take you away from enjoying the life that you have been given because it is your life for you to live. not to live it with pain and sorrow. i understand it‚Äôs a process, but please know that are so many people like you, like me, like us, who are encouraging each other to know and understand that we do not have to be slaves of the past. our horrible experiences with sexual abuse and sexual assault should not dictate how we could live our lives. with determination, tears, heart and courage, we can overcome. i invite you to give the gift of life to yourself and liberate yourself from those chains that keeps us sick in our minds, in our hearts and in our soul.

please find the peace and healing that you deserve, because only you can give the gift of life to yourself. may our creator give you the strength to find the cure to the liberation of your soul.‚Äù ‚Äî bamby salcedo 
#believesurvivors #survivorloveletter #wontbeerased #trans #metoo
