text:
posting this as a note-to-self for myself and anyone else who needs the reminder. ‚ú®
.
.
so often we guilt ourselves for taking a stand, asserting a boundary, or doing something to protect our mental health. we prioritize the feelings of others over the safety of ourselves because we want to avoid conflict or don‚Äôt want to ‚Äúhurt someone‚Äôs feelings‚Äù. in the end we end up suffering more mentally and emotionally by repeatedly allowing someone to harm our mental health and that needs to stop. ‚ú®
.
.
last night i took a huge stance in addressing something that has been impacting me, my mental health, and my career for far too long. it was terrifying but it was also liberating. i took the first step towards reclaiming my freedom and extricating myself from a toxic situation. i don‚Äôt yet know how it will turn out but i am so grateful for the support network i have helping me through this scary and difficult time. ‚ú®
.
.
the decision to stand up for myself and speak out against the situation has caused me insurmountable angst, but i can honestly say that opening up to the right people who are going to help me find a solution has been essential in lessening my anxiety. i am holding true to my beliefs and advocating for my rights and my mental health. it isn‚Äôt always easy, but it sure as hell is worth it. ‚ú®
.
.
if you find yourself in a similar situation, please know that i am alongside you in the trenches. it can seem daunting and scary when you‚Äôre facing it alone, but i promise you that reaching out will make it feel more manageable. as my best friend always tells me... ‚Äúeverything is figure-out-able‚Äù. ‚ú®
.
.
be brave, warriors and don‚Äôt be afraid to set those boundaries and stick to them. ‚ú® #metoo

buy some art, add to your collection and help make history, in the spirit of defining love, for our communities/families/lovers, outside of rape culture. 
link in my bio. 
browse and bookmark your favorites now through 2/28.
bidding starts on 2/28.

text:
the problematic nature of john hughes movies:
‚Ä¢sixteen candles (1984): i hate this movie so much, each and every scene and dialogue hits me in my bones and enrages me. it's racist, homophobic and jokes about rape and even attempts rape. it encourages non-consensual sex and the problematic nature of all the teen characters in the movie. i don't understand how people credit this movie as a "classic" when clearly it's not.
.
‚Ä¢the breakfast club (1985): yes it's a true classic and yes it represents the youth properly and the problems they face. it's funny and has memorable characters but i do think that it didn't age properly and people just don't see it. the most visible problem is alison (ally sheedy)'s transformation at the end, showing that pink lipgloss and a dress will make a person more likeable and eventually make a jock's mouth water. another thing that i find very poorly handled was claire (molly ringwald) and bender (jedd nelson)'s relationship. bender clearly bullied/harassed claire verbally and looked under her skirt very inappropriately because he's an "edgy dude who doesn't play by the rules" but actually he romanticised claire and couldn't come in terms with it and to make things more worse he isn't even sorry about it and gets the girl at the end.
.
molly ringwald herself finds these movies to be problematic, and people might criticise her for talking about it after the #metoo movement. however, i watched sixteen candles before the movement and before i even knew about the problems in the industry and yet i disliked it and thought it was sending a poor message.
.
the reason why i'm talking about this now is because i've been questioning recently about the levels of toxicity that the art i consume contains. and is the cinema's fault for creating such problematic content or is it culture's fault for consuming and demanding problematic content?
.
and happy valentines day üëΩ‚úå
.

‚Ä¢the breakfast club (1985): yes it is a true classic and yes it represents the youth properly and the problems they face. it is funny and has memorable characters but i do think that it didn't age properly and people just do not see it. the most visible problem is alison (ally sheedy)'s transformation at the end, showing that pink lipgloss and a dress will make a person more likeable and eventually make a jock's mouth water. another thing that i find very poorly handled was claire (molly ringwald) and bender (jedd nelson)'s relationship. bender clearly bullied/harassed claire verbally and looked under her skirt very inappropriately because he's an "edgy dude who does not play by the rules" but actually he romanticised claire and couldn't come in terms with it and to make things more worse he is not even sorry about it and gets the girl at the end.
.
molly ringwald herself finds these movies to be problematic, and people might criticise her for talking about it after the #metoo movement. however, i watched sixteen candles before the movement and before i even knew about the problems in the industry and yet i disliked it and thought it was sending a poor message.
.
the reason why i am talking about this now is because i have been questioning recently about the levels of toxicity that the art i consume contains. and is the cinema's fault for creating such problematic content or is it culture's fault for consuming and demanding problematic content?
.
and happy valentines day üëΩ‚úå
.

text: to anyone whatever going through the .any phases of healing n shit, as is everyday, it's all temporary, pain, happiness, life. hope everyone's well, in good relationships and beyond that just as we are. in phase, happy to live here to a degree. never moving back, adjusting vigilantly. that word my coach taught me, vigilant, resilient. this has been a hard time for our country, destructive bully wrecking lives. vigilance is incredibly important to practice, the more people of any background practicing such, the better off as a whole i think we'll be. it's like a vaccination, the more people vaccinated, the lesser chance of an outbreak. if the 75% have the vaccine, 25% is protected. 25% have it, the 75% infected. vigilant in a living way, of coarse, just enough to replace the ignorance i suppose. have a nice day. #freepress #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors #vigilance

text:
ep 15 the theme of this podcast is, belief. right now in the united states we are a part of the #metoo movement. it is devastating for many many women to know that if they spoke up they would not be believed. while so many women have come forward to share their stories of sexual abuse and stand together there are still so many more that stay quiet. that live in fear lest they should be judged. sarah was brave enough to speak up. i thank her for those of us that stay silent. 
stories like sarah‚Äôs teach us so much. the sheer resilience of humans for one. but also i love knowing the ways she has dealt with bumping up against the walls she has hit over the years. the tools she has used for helping herself become the person she wants to be. not staying in the pool of depression or victimization that we can all get caught up in at times. 
this woman is a hero. like all the women i have interviewed on the gardenia project. they face daily, their demons and learn how to turn fear and self doubt into kindness and love.  thank you for sharing @ms.sarahkelly üôè

text:
valentines day is my rape-a-versy. during this time i was youth pastor at a local church. so i kept what had been done to myself for years. until it became difficult for me to build interpersonal relationships. men assumed if they knew: that i put myself in compromising situations, or i was easy. women said you got away so you didn't  have it as bad as me. honestly, if they were remotely interested in helping they didn't know what to do. it wasn't until someone reccomend i see a counselor that things began to get better. i wanted to share so other people who have experienced this.know they are not alone and there is opportunity for hope and healing. for loving words of encouragement, or prayer feel free to dm me.
have a happy safe valentine's day.
-determined to be more bold-

text_retweet:
#repost @metoosurvivorsmarch
„Éª„Éª„Éª
‚Äúdear survivor, healing is not a destination but a practice.‚Äù üíå by amita swadhin, director of mirror memoirs ‚ú® art by jess x snow & layqa nuna yawar ‚ú® #survivorloveletter  was founded by tani ikeda [description: a queer brown gender non-conforming survivor looks up into the night sky. inside their portrait is a burnt down forest and their little self hugging themselves as wildflowers bloom all of their body. the quote above is handwritten . ]

here is a beautiful excerpt from amita‚Äôs extended #survivorloveletter : ‚Äúeverything in nature is here to teach you, if you can learn to open to the lessons: the ocean is changed but not defined by an oil spill. the wind is changed but not defined by a nuclear explosion. the dog is changed but not defined by the fighting pit.
healing is not a destination, but a practice and an understanding. one day you will learn to wear your wounds instead of being led by them. your spirit will expand far past the edges of your pain. you will understand suffering as a universal human experience, and power as the ability to feel joy and pleasure despite what you have endured. 
most of all, your wounds will disrupt the experience of time as linear. you and i will be able to use them to connect across time and space, because the body (and the psyche) truly does keep the score. i will visit you many times over, integrating each moment of fear, by holding your hand, rocking you, letting you weep in my arms ‚Äì i will grow up to understand how to love you in all the ways you always needed and never received. 
one day i will look at old photos of you: skinny brown girl with the big head and bigger glasses, teeth too large, knees too skinned, hair too scraggly, gender too mixed ‚Äì and marvel that what once looked ugly and spoiled looks only precious and tender and beautiful. 
i will always be with you, just as you will always be with me, until each memory is felt and released, until we are truly one.‚Äù #believesurvivors #lgbtqia #queerart #queer #lgbtq #metoo #metoosurvivorsmarch

text:
hi, welcome, to traumatea. i would like to introduce this page on a special day. vday, a day to acknowledge the fight to end violence against women around the world. to know more about this day go to onebillionrising.org. 
second let‚Äôs discuss why i have infused ‚Äútrauma‚Äù and ‚Äútea‚Äù together to name this page. drinking tea has always been a tradition in the women of my family. since i can remember as a child, my mother, grandmother, aunts, and great aunts have gathered around a tea pot to discuss the good, bad, and the ugly with the healing powers of warm tea on the table to soothe any worries. also, in japanese cultures you see the broken tea cup filled with gold. trauma may break the tea cup but it is our resilience, strength, courage, vulnerability, transparency, tenacity, community, and authenticity which brings the pieces back glued with gold. survivorship is not an easy path to walk and can be very isolating at times. so i, as a survivor of sexual violence in different forms from my childhood to adulthood, have decided to create a restorative transparent account of my day to day experience in trauma recovery. the raw isolating, sometimes cheerful, empowering tale of the life of a rape survivor. 
it is my intention to be as authentic, transparent, and restorative in my truth through this page in order to maybe reach one person to take away a piece of that isolation. all the while educating our world on the prevention, causes, and rates of sexual violence. please feel free to direct message, comment, or express however you feel. i intend for this to be a safe space for exchange of healing energy. negativity and hatefulness will not be tolerated. #healing #trauma #survivor #endsexualviolence #feminist #metoo #traumahealing #restoration #itstime #strength #traumasurvivor #sexualviolencevictim #survivoroftrauma #ptsd #thetruthaboutptsd #survivingptsd #mentalhealthawareness #education #safeplace #openforum #transparency #energycreation #vday #onebillionrising #femaleempowerment

text:
#metoo for garment workers 
how are we standing in solidarity with the women who make our clothes?

one in three female garment workers in cambodia experienced sexual harassment in the past year. with 85% of the global garment workforce being female, sexual harassment and gender based violence is an issue that needs recognition and attention.

how as an industry can we challenge systemic behaviour doing harm to those we seek to empower?

join dr anu mundkur, head of gender equality, care australia @careaustralia as she discusses the business case for a safe and dignified workplace for the women who make our clothes.

early bird tickets available for one more week until friday 22. grab yours at the link in bio. üëÜüèΩ #legacyfashionsummit . . . .
